In France, voting has traditionally been a low tech experience: voters isolate themselves in a booth and put a oppressed paper sheet with their chosen candidate in an envelope.
After the officials have verified the identity of the voter, the elector places the envelope in the poll and signs the voting document.
French Electoral legislation codifies the approach quite strictly.
Since 1988, the polls have to be transparent so that voters and observers can see that there are no envelopes at the start of the vote and that no envelopes are added except those other than those of the competent voters.
Candidates can send representatives to witness each part of the process. In the evening, the votes of volunteers are counted under comprehensive supervision, and follow specific procedures.
