When a small group of living creatures (a small stock) is separated from the main stock they originate from (for example, if they move over a mountain range or river, or if they move to a new island so that they can not easily get back), they often end up in a different environment than the one they previously were in.
This new environment has other resources and other competitors, so to be a strong competitor, the new population needs different functions or adaptations than they needed before.
The indigenous people have not changed at all, they still need the same adjustments as before.
With time, when the new population begins to adapt to its new environment, they begin to look smaller and smaller as the second population.
Eventually, after thousands or even millions of years, the two populations will look so different that they cannot be called the same species.
We call this process specialization, which simply means the formation of new species. Specialization is an inevitable consequence and a very important part of evolution.
